"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765598","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>We are increasing spending on childcare to over £6 billion per year by 2019-20 which includes £1 billion a year to deliver 30 hours of free childcare and increase our hourly funding rates. Our new funding rates are based on our ‘Review of Childcare Costs’ which looked at both the current costs of childcare provision and the implications of future cost pressures facing the sector. The Review was described as “thorough and wide ranging” by the National Audit Office.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s total hourly funding rate for three- and four-year olds (national average to local authorities) increased from £4.56 to £4.94 in April 2017. This compares very favourably with research into the cost of childcare, published by Frontier Economics in July 2017, which shows that the mean hourly delivery cost of a three/four year old place was £3.72.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has also increased Small Business Rate Relief and provided authorities with funding to support £300m of discretionary business rates relief, which could be used to support local nurseries.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","106210","2017-10-16T11:49:15.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765598/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765598/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765598/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-06","Pre-school Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on adjusting the total budget allocation for the early years national funding formula to take account of inflation in 2017.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765599","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Department publishes information on supported housing lettings in the last column of table 1a of the published tables accompanying the release of <em>Social Housing Lettings in England</em>, last published in December 2016.</p><p>The tables are available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/social-housing-lettings-in-england-april-2015-to-march-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/social-housing-lettings-in-england-april-2015-to-march-2016</a>.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-16T15:56:42.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765599/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765599/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765599/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-06","Supported Housing: Tenancy Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many tenancies there have been in supported housing in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765600","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Government launched the Affordable Homes Programme 2016-21 in April 2016. Initial allocations made by the Homes and Communities Agencies under the Programme can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/affordable-homes-programme-2016-to-2021-successful-bidders" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/affordable-homes-programme-2016-to-2021-successful-bidders</a></p><p>The Programme is delivered by the Greater London Authority (GLA) in London. The GLA launched the Homes for Londoners: Affordable Homes Programme 2016-21 in November 2016. Initial allocations made by the GLA can be found at: <a href="https://www.london.gov.uk/press-releases/mayoral/record-17bn-deal-for-new-homes" target="_blank">https://www.london.gov.uk/press-releases/mayoral/record-17bn-deal-for-new-homes</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-19T13:44:27.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765600/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765600/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765600/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-06","Affordable Housing and Shared Ownership Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much earmarked for the Shared Ownership and Affordable Homes Programme has been spent since the scheme was announced in the Spending Review 2015.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765601","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-16","<p>The number of non-decent local authority homes in London was 93,305 in 2010/11 and has fallen by over 57 per cent to 39,978 in 2015/16.</p><p>The number of non-decent private registered provider homes in London was 6,967 in 2010/11 and has fallen by over 78 per cent to 1,449 in 2015/16</p><p>Figures on the number of local authority owned non-decent homes at local authority level are available in the local authority housing statistics section F.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2015-to-2016</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2014-to-2015</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2013-to-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2013-to-2014</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2012-to-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2012-to-2013</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2011-to-2012" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-housing-statistics-data-returns-for-2011-to-2012</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/business-plan-statistical-appendix-bpsa-data-returns-for-2010-11" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/business-plan-statistical-appendix-bpsa-data-returns-for-2010-11</a></p><p><br>Figures on the number of private registered provider non-decent homes at local authority level in the stock information by local authority section of the HCAs statistical data return.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-data-return-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-data-return-2015-to-2016</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-data-return-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-data-return-2014-to-2015</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-data-return-2013-to-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-data-return-2013-to-2014</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-data-return-2012-to-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-data-return-2012-to-2013</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-data-return-2011-to-2012" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-data-return-2011-to-2012</a></p><p> </p><p>For data prior to 2011/12 figures are available in the Regulatory and Statistical Return (RSR11_0_Detail Tab)</p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120403140012/http:/www.tenantservicesauthority.org/server/show/ConWebDoc.21432" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120403140012/http://www.tenantservicesauthority.org/server/show/ConWebDoc.21432</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-16T10:48:28.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765601/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765601/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765601/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-06","Social Rented Housing: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many (a) local authority and (b) housing association homes in each of London's local authority areas have not met the decent homes standard in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","105845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765602","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Department does not currently collect administrative data on the number of people who are eligible for housing benefit and who moved into supported housing in 2016-17.</p><p> </p><p>Developing a workable and sustainable funding model for supported housing is a priority for the Government. We will set out further details on the Government’s plans later in the autumn.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-11T15:59:35.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765602/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765602/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765602/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-06","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of people who moved into supported housing in 2016-17 are eligible for housing benefit.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765603","Department of Health","false","2017-10-16","<p>Official statistics are published by NHS England on a monthly basis in respect of National Health Service performance against waiting times standards. This information is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-16T12:06:43.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765603/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765603/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765603/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Health Services: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which NHS operational standards have not been met during the period from May 2015 to date.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765604","Home Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>The policy was extended on 31 August for a further three months to give survivors additional time to come forward to receive support for the exceptionally traumatic events that they have experienced and to provide essential first-hand accounts regarding the fire.</p><p>This is a targeted immigration policy that we expect to benefit a limited number of people. The scheme has only been operating since 5 July and the extension to 30 November will provide a further opportunity for people to come forward. We have plans to publish statistics in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-12T09:17:30.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765604/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765604/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765604/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 3 August 2017 to Question 2332, how many people directly affected by the Grenfell Tower fire have been granted 12 months limited leave to remain.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765605","Department of Health","false","2017-10-16","<p>The following table shows the number of available nurse training places by year, for the period 2010-11 to 2016-17.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nurse total</p></td><td><p>20,138</p></td><td><p>17,903</p></td><td><p>17,442</p></td><td><p>18,056</p></td><td><p>19,206</p></td><td><p>20,153</p></td><td><p>20,680</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Health Education England (HEE) since 2013. Financial Information Management System prior to 2013.</p><p> </p><p>Pre-registration nurse training places will no longer be commissioned in the same way that has been done previously by HEE. The reforms for healthcare education funding from August 2017 will mean students will move onto the student loans system; giving universities the flexibility to provide additional places, based on local need and National Health Service clinical capacity. HEE will continue to fund the required number of clinical placements to meet the longer-term NHS workforce needs.</p><p> </p><p>On 3 October 2017, my Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health announced a 25% increase in undergraduate nurse training places which will be available to students from 2018. We are going beyond what was announced in Spending Review 2015 and August 2017 of an additional 10,000 places announced in 2015. The Government commitment means additional undergraduate nurse training places of up to 15,510 in England by the end of 2020/21</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-16T12:01:30.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765605/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765605/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765605/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Nurses: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many training posts for nurses were commissioned in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","105853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765606","Department of Health","false","2017-10-12","<p>Health Education England publish information on the number of general practice training places commissioned and filled.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of general practice training places commissioned and filled for the last three years can be found here:</p><p> </p><p>2016:</p><p><a href="https://gprecruitment.hee.nhs.uk/Portals/8/Documents/Annual%20Reports/GP%20ST1%20Recruitment%20Figures%202016.pdf?ver=2016-10-20-125603-367" target="_blank">https://gprecruitment.hee.nhs.uk/Portals/8/Documents/Annual%20Reports/GP%20ST1%20Recruitment%20Figures%202016.pdf?ver=2016-10-20-125603-367</a></p><p>2015:</p><p><a href="https://gprecruitment.hee.nhs.uk/Portals/8/Documents/Annual%20Reports/GP%20ST1%20Recruitment%20Figures%202015.pdf?ver=2015-12-18-140824-470" target="_blank">https://gprecruitment.hee.nhs.uk/Portals/8/Documents/Annual%20Reports/GP%20ST1%20Recruitment%20Figures%202015.pdf?ver=2015-12-18-140824-470</a></p><p>2014:</p><p><a href="https://gprecruitment.hee.nhs.uk/Portals/8/Documents/Annual%20Reports/GP%20ST1%20Recruitment%20Figures%202014.pdf?ver=2015-12-18-140824-470" target="_blank">https://gprecruitment.hee.nhs.uk/Portals/8/Documents/Annual%20Reports/GP%20ST1%20Recruitment%20Figures%202014.pdf?ver=2015-12-18-140824-470</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-12T12:40:29.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765606/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765606/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765606/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","General Practitioners: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many general practice speciality training posts were (a) commissioned and (b) filled in (i) 2014-15, (ii) 2015-16 and (iii) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","105854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765607","Department of Health","false","2017-10-13","<p>NHS England and NHS Digital do not hold data on the average number of hours spent on administrative tasks each week by general practitioners (GPs). NHS England is spending £45 million to train clerical staff to safely handle more paperwork without burdening the GP. Practices are already telling NHS England about the positive impact of this, with many saving nearly one hour per GP per day.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-13T10:33:37.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765607/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765607/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765607/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","General Practitioners: Administration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the average number of hours spent on administrative tasks each week by GPs in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","105848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765608","Department of Health","false","2017-10-12","<p>My Rt. Hon. Friend the Secretary of State has visited the following hospitals since 9 June 2017.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Royal Liverpool University Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Bournemouth Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Poole General Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dorset County Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Southampton General Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Queen Alexandra Hospital, Portsmouth</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Weston General Hospital, Weston-Super-Mare</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Devon and Exeter Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North Devon District Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Torbay Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Cornwall Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Derriford Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wigan Infirmary</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Southport and Formby District General Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Preston Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Blackpool Victoria Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Lancaster Infirmary</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cumberland Infirmary</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Medway Maritime Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Darent Valley Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Basildon University Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>St Peter’s Hospital, Chertsey</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Frimley Park Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Surrey County Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Victoria Infirmary, Newcastle</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South Tyneside District Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sunderland Royal Hospital</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hopewood Park Hospital, Sunderland</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Queen Elizabeth Hospital, Gateshead</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hexham General Hospital</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-12T12:52:55.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765608/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765608/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765608/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Hospitals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which hospitals he has visited in an official capacity since 9 June 2017.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","105847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765609","Department of Health","false","2017-10-16","<p>NHS England's plans to commission the new genomic laboratory infrastructure in October 2018 remain on course.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-16T12:31:12.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765609/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765609/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765609/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Down's Syndrome: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 18 July 2017 to Question 3971 on Down's syndrome: screening, whether NHS England's plans to go live with new genomic laboratory infrastructure remains on course.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765610","Department of Health","false","2017-10-16","<p>Funding for the North West London Sustainability and Transformation Plan area is £3.7 billion in 2017/18. Between 2015-16 and 2020-21 it is expected to rise by £602.5 million – a cash increase of 17%.</p><p> </p><p>We are keenly aware that local issues exist within the context of overall plans, but as with all public services, local National Health Service areas need to live within their means. NHS England and NHS Improvement will continue to work with a small number of areas who could do more to balance their financial plans, as many already have.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS has worked hard to manage its finances in a challenging period, reporting significant improvements compared to previous years. The overall deficit, the size of individual deficits and the number of trusts reporting a deficit, are all significantly down.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-16T12:27:41.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765610/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765610/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765610/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Health Services: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the financial sustainability of NHS services in north west London.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765611","Department of Health","false","2017-10-16","<p>Health Education England (HEE) has launched a successful campaign on their Return to practice programmes. These programmes are key to ensuring the National Health Service makes it as simple and flexible as possible for those that have left the workforce to return. Since the programme began in 2014 the number of nurses that have successfully completed the course and are now ready to enter employment stands at 3,596 (this is from September 2014 to March 2017).</p><p> </p><p>HEE does not collect data on the numbers that have returned to employment.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-16T12:15:32.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765611/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765611/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765611/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Nurses: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many nurses have (a) participated in the Return to Practice programme and (b) subsequently returned to practice within the NHS in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765612","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Discretionary Housing Payment fund is not a benefit, but is available to people in receipt of either Housing Benefit or the housing element of Universal Credit if they need further financial help with housing costs. This includes helping with such things as rent deposits and removal costs as well as mitigating the impact of welfare reform.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These payments are discretionary and are made by local authorities who have a duty to act fairly and reasonably when considering applications. The Department does however provide on line guidance to Local Authorities in England and Wales. Local authorities also provide voluntary monitoring returns to the Department twice yearly on how these payments have been allocated. Details of the 2016/17 End of Year statistical monitoring returns can be found below:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/576787/discretionary-housing-payments-guide.pdf" target="_blank"><strong>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/576787/discretionary-housing-payments-guide.pdf</strong></a></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-11T15:27:54.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765612/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765612/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-06","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what guidance his Department provides to local authorities on administration of discretionary housing benefit; and what steps his Department is taking to monitor the effectiveness of delivery of that benefit to those most in need.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765613","Department for Education","false","2017-10-14","<p>The Department for Education has noted the publication of the Sutton Trust’s report “<em>Closing Gaps Early</em>’’ (September 2017) on the role of early years policy in promoting social mobility in England. My officials will consider the research findings and recommendations.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-14T11:51:18.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765613/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765613/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-06","Children: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will respond to the recommendations of the report by the Sutton Trust entitled Closing Gaps Early, published in September 2017.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","106011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765614","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-11","<p>The latest available information on Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) clearance times can be found in the ESA Outcomes of Work Capability Assessments quarterly statistics published here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/employment-and-support-allowance-outcomes-of-work-capability-assessment" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/employment-and-support-allowance-outcomes-of-work-capability-assessment</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-10-11T14:35:12.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765614/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765614/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765614/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-06","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average time was for a decision being reached on a claim for employment and support allowance in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","105970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765615","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Food for Life Catering Mark is awarded to suppliers in the food service sector, not to Government Departments and Agencies.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-11T14:42:18.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765615/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765615/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-06","Government Departments: Catering","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which Government departments and agencies have achieved the Food for Life catering award.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","106155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765616","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-16","<p>The council tax system in England does not exclude Open University students from being eligible for council tax discounts. If such students meet the eligibility criteria that apply to any council tax discount, they will qualify for it.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","106129","2017-10-16T16:00:30.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765616/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765616/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-06","Council Tax: Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, why Open University students do not qualify for council tax discounts; and whether he plans to review this policy.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","106139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765617","Department for Work and Pensions","true","2017-10-12","<p>Calculation of a child maintenance liability is based on gross income information provided directly to the Child Maintenance Service by HMRC. <del class="ministerial">Individuals are required to declare unearned income not taxed at source which does not exceed £2500 a year to HMRC, which already enables HMRC to include it in the income information they provide.</del> Unearned income exceeding £2500 a year is dealt with by HMRC through tax self-assessment <del class="ministerial">and is picked up in a child maintenance calculation through an unearned income variation. We have no plans to review this.</del><ins class="ministerial">The treatment of unearned income for child maintenance purposes is aligned with this for administrative efficiency. We are inviting views on the future treatment of &quot;income&quot; within the recently published Compliance and Arrears Strategy consultation.</ins></p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2017-10-12T13:56:00.367Z","2018-02-01T17:10:55.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765617/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765617/answer","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765617/answer/previousversion/14051","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-06","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, why the Child Maintenance Service allows non-resident parents £2,500 of unearned income that is not factored into payment plans; and whether he plans to review this policy.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","106137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765618","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-16","<p>The council tax system in England does not exclude Open University students from being eligible for council tax discounts. If such students meet the eligibility criteria that apply to any council tax discount, they will qualify for it.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","106139","2017-10-16T16:00:30.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765618/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765618/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-06","Council Tax: Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the (a) effect on living standards and (b) equity of Open University students being ineligible for council tax discounts.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","106129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765619","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-16","<p>On 2 October my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State announced the appointment of the first Small Business Commissioner, who will tackle unfair payment practices by providing general information and advice, direct small businesses to existing services and handle complaints about payment issues, thus supporting Britain’s 5.5 million small businesses. Our small businesses are the backbone of our economy, and removing barriers to their growth is a key part of a dynamic, market economy. Our Industrial Strategy will ensure a competitive market that supports new businesses and innovation.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-16T12:51:50.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765619/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765619/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765619/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-06","Small Business Commissioner: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what role the Small Business Commissioner plays in the formation and delivery of UK industrial strategy.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","106138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765620","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Employment Allowance allows business and charities throughout the UK to reduce their employer National Insurance contributions (NICs) bill by up to £3,000 every year. Last year alone this meant over 1 million employers benefitted, of which 97% had fewer than 50 employees. Employers overall saved £2bn in employers NICs due to the Employment Allowance.</p><p> </p><p>The Government published research into awareness and impact of the Employment Allowance with small employers in 2015. This can be found online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/445848/Research_Report_368_Awareness_and_Impact_of_the_Employment_Allowance_-_Research_with_small_employers.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/445848/Research_Report_368_Awareness_and_Impact_of_the_Employment_Allowance_-_Research_with_small_employers.pdf</a></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-11T11:33:09.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765620/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765620/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-06","National Insurance Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of his Department's policy on employment allowance on (a) employment and (b) small and medium-sized enterprises; and whether he plans to amend the employment allowance policy.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","106157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765621","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Government knows how important tackling late payment is, especially for smaller businesses and has previously announced a package of measures to improve payment practices across the public and private sector.</p><p>The Reporting on Payment Practices and Performance Regulations 2017 came in to force this year. This statutory requirement increases transparency, providing small and medium-sized businesses with better information about large businesses they intend to trade with.</p><p>The Small Business Commissioner, created by the Enterprise Act 2016, will empower small businesses to tackle late payment; providing general advice and information to small businesses on matters such as resolving payment disputes.</p><p>The Public Contracts Regulations 2015, mandate that public sector buyers must include 30-day payment terms in new public sector contracts; and requires that this payment term be passed down the supply chain.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-11T14:40:13.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765621/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765621/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-06","Small Businesses: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what action the Government is taking to ensure timely payments to small and medium-sized enterprises; and whether he plans to introduce legislation to ensure that payments to small and medium-sized enterprises are timely.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","106156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765622","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Government knows how important tackling late payment is, especially for smaller businesses. The 2016 Impact Assessment for the Duty to report on payment practices and performance provides further detail on the assessment of the impact of late payment on small and medium-sized enterprises and can be found here - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/business-payment-practices-and-policies-duty-to-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/business-payment-practices-and-policies-duty-to-report</a>.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-11T13:26:16.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765622/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765622/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-06","Small Businesses: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of late payments on small and medium-sized enterprises.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","106158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765623","Home Office","false","2017-10-18","<p>All Home Office contracts are tendered in compliance with the EU Procurement Directives, which ensure that there is a transparent and equitable procurement process.</p><p>The project that is putting in place contracts to replace the current suite of contracts from 2019, will be utilising the Competitive Procedure with Negotiation procedure. This allows the contracting authority the opportunity to negotiate with short-listed bidders in a structured manner before inviting final tenders.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-18T14:23:14.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765623/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765623/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government plans to revise the process for awarding contracts to private companies for the provision of accommodation for asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","106322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765624","Home Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>Accommodation providers are required to provide safe, habitable, fit for purpose and correctly equipped accommodation that complies with the Decent Homes Standard in addition to standards outlined in relevant national or local housing legislation.</p><p>The contract requires Providers to visit and inspect each property every month and UKVI inspects a significant proportion of properties each year to ensure standards are being met. Where asylum accommodation is found to be falling short of the required standards UKVI has procedures in place to inspect, investigate and quickly resolve when specific information is received and a contract management regime to monitor supplier performance and take measures where appropriate.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-16T15:10:08.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765624/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765624/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what measures are in place to ensure that private subcontractors providing accommodation for asylum seekers are meeting the standards of the Housing Act and that such measures are enforced and complaints acted on.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","106323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765625","Home Office","false","2017-10-25","<p>The Government demands the highest standards and integrity from our contractors at all times and the Home Office monitor them closely to ensure their accommodation and service meets the requirements set out in the contracts. The Home Office has worked closely with all our Providers, to improve property standards over the lifetime of the contracts.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-25T16:26:48.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765625/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765625/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what undertakings has G4S made to improve service in relation to accommodation for asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","106324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765626","Home Office","false","2017-10-25","<p>Property standards under COMPASS are monitored by three key performance indicators to ensure it is safe, habitable and fit for purpose. Non-conformance occurs when the defects are not rectified within the agreed contractual timescales. Where there is any instance of non-conformance the performance indicators are applied which may lead to a financial deduction.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-25T16:00:29.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765626/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765626/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, in how many of the last 12 months G4S has met its KPIs for providing accommodation for asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","106325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765627","Home Office","false","2018-04-24","<p>The Home Office and our accommodation providers take complaints extremely seriously and have robust procedures in place to inspect, investigate and resolve when specific information is received. In the first instance, issues with Asylum Accommodation should be reported to the relevant Provider, for them to resolve. Where a Provider does not resolve a complaint satisfactorily, or the response is considered inadequate, then the complaint can be brought directly to UKVI, including via Migrant Help or another representative. Our records show that between October 2016 and October 2017 UKVI have received 68 complaints concerning G4S service to asylum seekers. These figures are based on local management information. This information has not been quality assured under National Statistics protocols, is subject to change and should be treated as provisional.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-04-24T15:36:43.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765627/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765627/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many complaints have been made against G4S in the last year on its service to asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","106326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765628","Home Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Home Office closely monitors the movement of all asylum seekers by accommodation providers, however historic statistics on the number of people who have been relocated from dispersed accommodation more than four times in a year could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p>All relocation requests are monitored by UKVI and no individual will be moved on more than two occasions within a twelve month period unless there are exceptional circumstance.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-16T15:05:43.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765628/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765628/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum seekers have been moved more than four times in a year by (a) G4S and (b) other providers of accommodation for asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","106327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765629","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-11","<p>No discussions were held with either EDF Energy or CGN before the 29 July 2016 or after 15 September 2016 on the potential financial consequences for them of the decision to delay the approval of Hinkley Point C.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-10-11T14:39:54.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765629/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765629/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-06","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions his officials have had with EDF Energy and CGN Energy (a) before 29 July 2016 and (b) after 15 September 2016 on the potential financial consequences for those companies of the decision to delay approval of Hinkley Point C.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","106160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765630","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>The estimate of the Whole Life Costs for Hinkley Point C in the major project portfolio data is £49,891.2m. The Whole Life Costs are determined by the difference between the Strike Price and the long-term Wholesale Electricity Price forecasts, which are influenced by market prices for fossil fuels, which may vary.</p><p> </p><p>The Whole Life Cycle costs have been calculated in nominal terms and have not been discounted.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-10-12T13:47:51.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765630/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765630/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765630/answer/previousversion/13873","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-06","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will provide a breakdown of the estimate of the total whole life costs for Hinkley Point C in the major project portfolio data published in September 2016.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","106161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765631","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Government is absolutely clear that victims of domestic violence must have access to the help that they need, including access to legal aid.</p><p>The existing regulations make clear that, for the purpose of the domestic violence evidence requirements for legal aid, a “health professional” means a registered (a) medical practitioner who holds a license to practice; b) nurse; (c) midwife; or (d) practitioner psychologist who holds a licence to practice. Evidence from a health visitor will be accepted providing that they are a qualified nurse, midwife or licensed practitioner psychologist.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-12T15:01:19.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765631/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765631/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-06","Legal Aid Scheme: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department accepts health visitors as suitable professionals to complete and sign the letter Response from health professional to request for evidence of injuries/condition consistent with domestic violence in pursuit of the granting of legal aid.","false","Biography information for Rosie Duffield","Canterbury","Rosie Duffield","106305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765632","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Department announced these changes in a response to consultation published on 16 December 2016. The Domestic Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme (Amendment) (No. 2) Regulations 2017 were laid on 30 August 2017 and came into force on 20 September 2017.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-10-17T15:42:49.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765632/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765632/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-06","Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what notice period his Department gave to the industry before the Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme and Domestic Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme (Amendment) (No. 2) Regulations 2017 came into force.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","105813"
