"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765646","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-19","<p>Until 2016, Defra published data on the estimated number of seasonal agricultural workers in all UK countries in “Agriculture in the UK”, which is a Defra publication. Since 2016, data is published for England only, collected by the June Horticulture and Agriculture Survey. Data from the past 5 years is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>Defra does not collect data on the nationality of those workers.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Seasonal, casual &amp; gang labour</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK numbers</p></td><td><p><strong>67 000</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>61 000</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>66 000</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>67 000</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>N/A</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England-only numbers</p></td><td><p><strong>44 985</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 39 203</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>43 036</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>44 939</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>43 894</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-19T14:57:13.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765646/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765646/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-06","Agriculture: Seasonal Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the number of (a) non-UK EU and (b) other seasonal agricultural workers who have come to the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Helen Whately","Faversham and Mid Kent","Helen Whately","106264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765647","Department for Education","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Study of Early Education and Development (SEED): the potential value for money of early education, published in July 2017, used the Study of Early Education and Development (SEED): The cost and funding of early education report, published January 2017. This report calculated the hourly delivery cost of years funding for 3 to 4-year olds. The mean hourly cost for 3 to 4-year-olds place was £3.65 in the east of England. The median and modal averages were not stated in the report.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","105967","2017-10-11T16:26:03.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765647/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765647/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-06","Pre-school Education: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the report entitled Study of early education and development: the potential value for money of early education, published in July 2017, what the median hourly delivery cost was in early years funding for a three-four-year old place in the east of England.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr  Dan Poulter","105968"
