"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765740","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-16","<p>All Remotely Piloted Air Systems (RPAS) operated by the Armed Forces are controlled from the ground.</p><p>There have been no recorded accidents involving RAF RPAS at West Wales Airport, Aberporth.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-16T14:49:21.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765740/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765740/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765740/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-06","Unmanned Air Vehicles: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many recorded accidents involving RAF pilotless drones have occured at Aberporth Airport.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","105846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765741","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-16","<p>All Remotely Piloted Air Systems (RPAS) operated by the Armed Forces are controlled from the ground. The Armed Forces undertake routine flying activity on RPAS at the following locations:</p><p>UK:</p><p>Boscombe Down, Wiltshire.</p><p>Lulworth Cove Traning Area, Dorset.</p><p>Okehampton Training Area, Dartmoor.</p><p>Otterburn Training Area, Northumberland.</p><p>RAF Spadeadam, Cumbria.</p><p>Royal Naval Air Station, Culdrose.</p><p>Salisbury Plain Training Area, Wiltshire.</p><p>Sennybridge Training Area, Wales.</p><p>Stanford Training Area, Norfolk.</p><p>West Wales Airport &amp; Aberporth Range.</p><p>Overseas:</p><p>British Army Training Unit, Kenya.</p><p>British Army Training Unit Suffield, Canada.</p><p>Camp Roberts, California, USA.</p><p>Creech Air Force Base, Nevada, USA.</p><p>Grafenwohr Training Area, Germany.</p><p>Hohenfels Training Area, Germany.</p><p>Holloman Air Force Base, New Mexico, USA.</p><p>Sennelager Training Area, Germany.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-16T14:52:07.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765741/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765741/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765741/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-06","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, at which locations the Armed Forces' pilot-less drones are flown for training purposes.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","106051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765742","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-16","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will make sure that the body of existing EU environmental law continues to have effect in UK law followed by the introduction of secondary legislation as required. This will include regulations linked to CITES. Any future changes will be updated through secondary legislation.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-10-16T12:17:56.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765742/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765742/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765742/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-06","Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what mechanism will beused to ensure that UK domestic legislation captures changes to CITES when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","106378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765743","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Ministry is committed to ensuring the justice system is supported by a range of high quality language services that meet the needs of all those that require them. Provisions for non-spoken languages, including sign language interpreters, are met through the Ministry’s language services contract with Clarion Interpreting Ltd.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-16T15:14:55.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765743/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765743/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765743/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-06","Courts: Sign Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what provision there is for sign language interpreters to be available for people registered as deaf who are involved in court trials.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","105732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765744","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-18","<p>The Jury Central Summoning Bureau is not aware at point of summons of any potential disabilities. Replies to summonses, where this information is provided to the Jury Central Summoning Bureau, are only kept for twelve months. Reviewing these replies would not provide data for the five years requested and would not provide a complete data set (as telephone and email responses are not recorded). This information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-18T16:15:08.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765744/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765744/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765744/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-06","Juries: Hearing Impaired","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what information his Department holds on the number of people registered as deaf who are called for jury service in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","105733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765745","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-15","<p>The Ministry of Justice (MoJ) regularly seek advice from relevant experts as we work to respond to the individual needs of those under our supervision and in our care including those registered as deaf. We are proactively looking at ways to ensure our workforce is even more diverse and representative of the people we serve so that customer needs are met both now and in the future. The Equalities and Inclusion Engagement Group sits quarterly; the main aim of this group is to collaborate positively with HM Courts and Tribunals Service (HMCTS) to review aspects of the proposed Court reform. This ensures we integrate equality principles into all reformed services, promoting a service that is inclusive, user focussed, and that does not discriminate against the vulnerable or disadvantaged. HMCTS have a standing arrangement with the Disabilities Charity Consortium (of which Action on Hearing Loss are a member), that agendas are shared in advance of meetings to ensure that when relevant items are upcoming that are of importance to member charities they can either join the meeting, feed in via or other members that are attending, or share input directly with HMCTS.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-15T16:32:23.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765745/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765745/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765745/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-06","Administration of Justice: Hearing Impaired","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions he has had with charities for the deaf on the service received by people registered as deaf in the justice system.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","105731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765746","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-16","<p>There are no current plans to amend the Juries Act 1974.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-16T15:14:38.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765746/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765746/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765746/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-06","Juries: Sign Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he has made an assessment of the potential merits of bringing forward proposals to amend the Juries Act 1974 to allow for a sign language interpreter not to be considered as an extra juror.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","105730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765747","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-16","<p>Where a property is occupied by a charity and used for charitable purposes they will usually receive a mandatory 80 per cent relief from rates, which can be increased to 100 per cent at the discretion of the local billing authority. Unlike small businesses, charities qualify for this relief irrespective of their occupation of other properties or the rateable value of the property.</p><p>The Government fully recognises the important public benefit that charities bring to communities, and charities also enjoy a range of additional tax benefits on their operations that businesses do not.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-16T10:38:12.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765747/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765747/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765747/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-06","Non-domestic Rates: Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what measures the Government plans to introduce to ensure that small charities are not treated less favourably than other small businesses in relation to their liability for non-domestic rates.","false","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng","106218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765748","Department of Health","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Government has committed to providing a further update to the House after the consultation closes on 18 October. This update will include a summary of responses to the consultation received. All consultation responses will be passed on to the independent inquiry once established.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-10-16T15:13:01.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765748/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765748/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765748/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish all responses received by the current inquiry into infected blood.","false","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng","106270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765749","Department of Health","false","2017-10-11","<p>Information is not held in the format requested.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-11T16:11:17.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765749/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765749/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765749/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Dental Services: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average payment per unit of dental activity for dental practices is in (a) Stockton on Tees, (b) the North East and (c) England.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","106309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765750","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-13","<p>Claims data is not recorded in a way which identifies claims by secondary victims. When compensation claims are received they are considered on the basis of whether or not the Ministry of Defence has a legal liability to pay compensation. Where there is a legal liability to pay compensation we do so.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-10-13T13:05:03.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765750/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765750/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765750/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-06","Ministry of Defence: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many secondary victims claims have been made against his Department in each of the last 10 years; how many of those claims were successful; how many claimants have undergone psychiatric assessment as part of that process; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","106016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765751","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-13","<p>Claims data is not recorded in a way which identifies claims in which Courts awarded punitive or exemplary damages against the Department in cases involving the death of military personnel. It is, however, believed that there have been no cases at all in the last 10 years.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-10-13T13:04:17.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765751/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765751/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765751/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-06","Armed Forces: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many awards have been made for claims of punitive damages in cases of death of military personnel in each of the last 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","106017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765752","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-16","<p>Volunteer Gliding Squadron courses are allocated on a rolling basis and vary according to requirements between longer Silver Wings Courses and shorter Blue/Bronze Wings courses. Consequently, the total number of course places available is not programmed in advance. However, it is envisaged to be greatly expanded in 2018, compared to 2017.</p><p>In addition, we are expanding other aspects of the Cadet Aviation Offer, including to provide additional civilian gliding experience at up to 14 civil gliding sites, powered flying opportunities at RAF Flying Club Association clubs, enhanced synthetic training at the Regional Aerospace Ground Schools and more musters of cadets to fly as passengers in military helicopters and larger military aircraft.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-10-16T14:15:16.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765752/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765752/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765752/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-06","Armed Forces: Gliding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many places on Volunteer Gliding Squadron courses will be available in 2018; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","106130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765753","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-16","<p>Since November 2014, 95 acres of acacia have been removed from Special Areas of Conservation in the Sovereign Base Areas (SBA). In addition, the SBA Administration has been pursuing other means of acacia removal beyond physical tree cutting, including destroying 5.8km of irrigation piping used to promote growth of acacia on the Cape Pyla Ranges in the Dhekelia SBA.</p><p>We plan to remove further acreage of invasive acacia from Special Areas of Conservation in the SBA of Akrotiri and Dhekelia. No decision has yet been made on the specific sites where acacia could be removed and treated with herbicide to prevent re-growth. This will be subject to risk assessment.</p><p>Further consideration of options to remove acacia and associated irrigation will take place following this year's migration.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-10-16T14:53:31.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765753/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765753/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765753/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-06","Cyprus: Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans his Department has to remove invasive Australian acacia trees from the Sovereign Base Areas of (a) Akrotiri and (b) Dhekelia in (i) the remaining months of 2017 and (ii) thereafter; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","105742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765754","Department of Health","false","2017-10-16","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has assessed the clinical and cost-effectiveness of silver-based catheters versus hydrophilic and silicone catheters in reducing healthcare-associated urinary tract infections in both primary and secondary settings.</p><p> </p><p>The guidance is available here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/researchrecommendation/indwelling-urinary-catheters-catheter-selection-for-patients-using-a-long-term-indwelling-urinary-catheter-what-is-the-clinical-and-cost-effectiveness-of-impregnated-versus-hydrophilic-versus-silicone-catheters-in-reducing-symptomatic-urinary-tract-infect" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/researchrecommendation/indwelling-urinary-catheters-catheter-selection-for-patients-using-a-long-term-indwelling-urinary-catheter-what-is-the-clinical-and-cost-effectiveness-of-impregnated-versus-hydrophilic-versus-silicone-catheters-in-reducing-symptomatic-urinary-tract-infect</a></p><p> </p><p>This NICE guidance revealed a gap in the evidence for the effectiveness of indwelling catheters in the long term, with further evidence needed to assess the clinical and cost-effectiveness of silver-coated catheters.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-16T16:33:32.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765754/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765754/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765754/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Catheters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect of the use of silver-coated catheters in hospitals on (a) infection rates and (b) costs; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","106131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765755","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Department for Transport takes all possible measures to ensure that all states implement and enforce UN Security Council resolutions. Such measures can include engagement with partner states, and the UN Panel of Experts on the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea (DPRK), regarding the misuse of country flags by ships connected to the DPRK.</p><p> </p><p>UN Security Council resolutions call on Member States to de-register any vessel that is owned, operated or crewed by the DPRK, and not to register any such vessels that have been de-registered by another Member State. The ship registry of the UK fully complies with this measure.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","106018","2017-10-16T12:04:11.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765755/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765755/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765755/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-06","Shipping: North Korea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will detail the steps his Department is taking to ensure the close monitoring of ships registered to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea which change their (a) ship names, (b) flag, (c) company name and (d) reported beneficial owner; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","106019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765756","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Department for Transport takes all possible measures to ensure that all states implement and enforce UN Security Council resolutions. Such measures can include engagement with partner states, and the UN Panel of Experts on the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea (DPRK), regarding the misuse of country flags by ships connected to the DPRK.</p><p> </p><p>UN Security Council resolutions call on Member States to de-register any vessel that is owned, operated or crewed by the DPRK, and not to register any such vessels that have been de-registered by another Member State. The ship registry of the UK fully complies with this measure.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","106019","2017-10-16T12:04:11.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765756/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765756/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765756/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-06","Shipping: North Korea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking proactively to monitor Democratic People's Republic of Korea foreign-flagged ships in order to ensure enforcement of the mandate to inspect their cargo; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","106018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765757","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-16","<p>We are currently working with existing EU trading partners, including South Africa, to ensure that where preferential trading agreements are in place, arrangements are made that will allow maximum possible continuity in the effect of these agreements, when the UK leaves the EU. This is a technical exercise to ensure continuity in existing trading arrangements.</p><p>In this regard, we are engaging with trading partners to understand mutually beneficial options for ensuring the greatest continuity. Rules of Origin, as a key element of trade agreements, form an important part of this ongoing engagement.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","106339","2017-10-16T15:58:20.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765757/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765757/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765757/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-06","Trade Agreements: Rules of Origin","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he is having with (a) South Africa and (b) other countries that have an existing Free Trade Agreement with the EU on rules of origin or originating content issues arising from the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","106338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765758","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-16","<p>We are currently working with existing EU trading partners, including South Africa, to ensure that where preferential trading agreements are in place, arrangements are made that will allow maximum possible continuity in the effect of these agreements, when the UK leaves the EU. This is a technical exercise to ensure continuity in existing trading arrangements.</p><p>In this regard, we are engaging with trading partners to understand mutually beneficial options for ensuring the greatest continuity. Rules of Origin, as a key element of trade agreements, form an important part of this ongoing engagement.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","106338","2017-10-16T15:58:20.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765758/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765758/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765758/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-06","Trade Agreements: Rules of Origin","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will take steps for the UK to have third-party membership of existing EU Free Trade Agreements to comply with rules of origin requirements.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","106339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765759","Department of Health","false","2017-10-16","<p>In considering local commissioning for fertility services, clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) should have regard to clinical evidence within the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence Guidance for fertility services. There is no need for CCGs to undertake their own evidence reviews.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-16T12:32:57.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765759/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765759/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765759/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","In Vitro Fertilisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with clinical commissioning groups that have reportedly commissioned their own reviews of fertility services to inform commissioning practice.","false","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","106093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765760","Department of Health","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) has advised that it does not have any powers to regulate treatment which takes place outside the United Kingdom. It therefore holds no data on the number of patients who travel abroad for their treatment and is unable to assess the potential impact this may have on multiple birth rates. The HFEA provides information on its website advising patients of the risks of multiple pregnancies and suggesting that patients seeking treatment abroad should discuss these risks and how to minimise them with their overseas clinic.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-16T12:17:28.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765760/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765760/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765760/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","In Vitro Fertilisation: Multiple Births","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the potential increase in the number of people seeking IVF treatment abroad and the consequences of this for multiple birth rates.","false","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","106091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765761","Department of Health","false","2017-10-16","<p>The availability of National Health Service funded fertility treatment is and always has been a matter for local determination. Decisions on the level of service provision are made by clinical commissioning groups and underpinned by clinical insight and knowledge of local healthcare needs and priorities. The role of the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is to develop guidance and quality standards to drive quality improvements in health and care; NICE has already developed NICE Guidance for fertility services and Quality Standards for fertility problems.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-16T12:35:16.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765761/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765761/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765761/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","In Vitro Fertilisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will ask NICE's implementation team to look at methods by which access to NHS tertiary infertility services can be improved in England.","false","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","106092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765762","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-11","<p>We will close down ageing and ineffective prisons, replacing them with buildings fit for today’s demands. On 22 March 2017, my Rt Hon friend, the Lord Chancellor and Secretary of State for Justice announced plans for the building of four new prisons in England and Wales, replacing old and overcrowded establishments with new, fit for purpose buildings. The plans include a new prison in Port Talbot in South Wales.</p><p> </p><p>The Welsh Government notified the Ministry of Justice of potential sites, including the one at Port Talbot, on 3 May 2016.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","106166","2017-10-11T17:05:21.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765762/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765762/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765762/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-06","Prisons: South Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, on what date he first received communication from the Welsh Government identifying potential sites for a new prison in South Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765763","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-11","<p>We will close down ageing and ineffective prisons, replacing them with buildings fit for today’s demands. On 22 March 2017, my Rt Hon friend, the Lord Chancellor and Secretary of State for Justice announced plans for the building of four new prisons in England and Wales, replacing old and overcrowded establishments with new, fit for purpose buildings. The plans include a new prison in Port Talbot in South Wales.</p><p> </p><p>The Welsh Government notified the Ministry of Justice of potential sites, including the one at Port Talbot, on 3 May 2016.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","106167","2017-10-11T17:05:21.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765763/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765763/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765763/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-06","Prisons: Port Talbot","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, on what date he first received communication from the Welsh Government identifying the Port Talbot site for potential development as a new prison.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","106166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765764","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>The UK supports the Saudi-led Coalition military intervention, which came at the request of legitimate President Hadi, to deter aggression by the Houthis, and allow for the return of the legitimate Yemeni government. We are aware of reports of alleged violations of International Humanitarian Law (IHL) and we take these very seriously. It is important that credible allegations of violations of IHL are investigated. We regularly press the need for the Saudi-led Coalition to conduct thorough and conclusive investigations into reports of alleged violations of IHL. Saudi Arabia has publicly stated that it is investigating reports of alleged violations of IHL, and that lessons will be acted upon. We welcome the reports issued by the Joint Incidents Assessment Team, including the 15 reports issued on 12 September (taking the total number to 36). We will continue to press the Saudi-led Coalition to demonstrate its commitment to IHL.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-16T16:18:56.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765764/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765764/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765764/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-06","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what plans he has to review his Department's policy towards Saudi Arabia as a result of alleged war crimes in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","105885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765765","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>Addressing the humanitarian crisis in Yemen is a key priority for the UK and we continue to raise the issue in regular Ministerial-level conversations with our regional and international partners. The Foreign Secretary raised the humanitarian situation in his discussion with the Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia on 25 August</p><p>The UK has also taken the lead in urging all parties to ensure rapid, safe and unhindered humanitarian access. This call was repeated by the UN Security Council Presidential Statement proposed and coordinated by the UK in June. This September at the UN General Assembly I hosted a Ministerial-level meeting with Saudi Arabia, the UAE, the US and UN Special Envoy for Yemen. All recognized the dire humanitarian situation and agreed that more must be done to alleviate immediate need.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-10-16T16:23:31.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765765/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765765/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765765/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-06","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Saudi counterpart on the challenges faced by humanitarian agencies delivering aid to Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","106067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765766","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-13","<p>In the light of the rapidly changing international situation and the intensification of the threats identified in the 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review, the Government is conducting a National Security Capability Review to ensure our capabilities are as effective and efficient as possible. Defence is playing a full role in this work - undertaken to look again at the specific capabilities available not just to the Ministry of Defence but across Government, to ensure that as threats intensify we continue to have the right capabilities in the right places to meet them.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-10-13T13:03:34.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765766/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765766/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765766/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-06","Strategic Defence and Security Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether he will conduct a new Strategic Defence and Security Review when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","105935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765767","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Government takes the threat of cyber attacks against public services very seriously. We support Health and Local Government sectors in improving their cyber resilience and encourage all organisations to implement the National Cyber Security Centre’s advice: to keep software patches up to date, to run antivirus and to back up their data.</p><p>In addition to this, the NCSC is developing Active Cyber Defence initiatives which will lead national efforts to block, disrupt and neutralise malicious cyber activity before it reaches our public services.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-16T14:38:47.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765767/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765767/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765767/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Public Sector: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to protect public services against cyber attacks.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","105883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765768","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>Workforce planning is primarily the responsibility of each department. The Civil Service<br>constantly reviews its capabilities in order to deliver the Government's commitment to<br>leave the EU and get the best deal for the UK. Civil Service HR is working with all<br>departments across the Civil Service to better understand their capacity and capability<br>requirements.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-16T14:33:42.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765768/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765768/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765768/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-06","Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the size of the Civil Service workforce.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","105884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765769","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-18","<p>G4S provide electronic monitoring hardware (tags and home monitoring units) under contract, to the Ministry of Justice, having ceased delivery of field services and monitoring operations in early 2014, when the contract was transferred to Capita. On 27 June 2017 G4S were awarded preferred bidder status for the next generation electronic monitoring hardware contract, with Capita continuing to provide the field services and monitoring operations. The contracts are subject to stringent specifications and the equipment has been rigorously tested to exacting performance standards. The Department has robust processes in place to monitor and manage contractors and will not hesitate to take action when standards fall short.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-18T16:05:59.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765769/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765769/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765769/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-06","Electronic Tagging: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he has taken to use contracts it has with G4S to improve the tagging performance of that company; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","106430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765770","Home Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>Her Majesty’s Passport Office (HM Passport Office) received 6,398,160 UK passport applications in 2014. In 2015 HM Passport Office received 6,946,504 applications and in 2016, HM Passport Office received 7,091,695 applications.</p><p> </p><p>I refer the Rt Hon. Member to the information in the attached link where applications are shown by month of intake.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmpo-transparency-data-august-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmpo-transparency-data-august-2017</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-16T15:01:01.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765770/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765770/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765770/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passport applications were received by HM Passport Office in (a) 2014, (b) 2015 and (c) 2016.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","106335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765771","Home Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>The specific data requested is not published by the Home Office.</p><p> </p><p>Published data on visa processing times, including the percentage of visas processed within published service standards, is published online at the following address: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data</a> (then listed by publication date under ‘UK Visas &amp; Immigration’).</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-17T15:31:39.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765771/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765771/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765771/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average length of time is for a visa to be issued for a visitor to the UK from a non-EU country in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","106331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765772","Home Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>Protecting the UK border is, and always has been, of paramount importance to this Government. It has never been government practice, for reasons of national security, to comment on operational issues relating to border security. This includes offering commentary on the performance of border systems and of eGates specifically.</p><p>There are currently 232 e-Passport gates operating across 12 UK airports.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-16T15:16:58.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765772/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765772/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765772/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Immigration Controls: Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many e-gates there are at each UK airport; and how many such gates were operational on 21 July 2017.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","106332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765773","Home Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>This information is not available.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-16T15:11:54.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765773/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765773/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765773/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the country of origin was of EU citizens applying for passports in (a) 2014, (b) 2015 and (c) 2016.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","106333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765774","Home Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>HM Passport Office does not statistical information on dual citizenship therefore we cannot provide the information requested.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-16T15:04:18.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765774/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765774/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765774/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Passports: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passport applicants were EU citizens in (a) 2014, (b) 2015 and (c) 2016.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","106334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765775","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-12","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade has met a number of defence companies since his appointment. The meetings have covered a range of topics, including the UK’s Exit from the European Union.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-12T11:50:10.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765775/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765775/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765775/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-06","Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many meetings he has had with representatives of UK arms manufacturers on the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","105933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765776","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-17","<p>All export licences are issued in strict accordance with the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria. The framework was announced to parliament by the former Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, the Rt. Hon Member for Twickenham, Sir Vince Cable, as a Written Ministerial Statement on 25 March 2014.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-17T12:38:43.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765776/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765776/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765776/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-06","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will review his Department's policy on arms sales to Saudi Arabia following alleged human rights violations in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","105881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765777","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Department provides strong support for the UK aerospace sector through the Aerospace Growth Partnership. We believe this has been successful in protecting the industry and supporting its growth. Since 2010, the UK aerospace industry has seen turnover grow from £23.7billion to £32billion; exports have increased from £18billion to £30billion; direct jobs have grown from 110,000 to 120,000, with indirect jobs up from 148,000 to 161,000; and, between 2010 and 2016, productivity growth in the sector was over five times more than in the economy as a whole. In addition we have created a more certain environment to drive increased investment in R&amp;D, through a £1.95billion Government commitment over 13 years to 2026, matched by industry, to fund new R&amp;D projects.</p><p>But we are not complacent and will continue to work with industry through the AGP to retain the UK's position as a leading aerospace nation.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-10-16T13:00:42.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765777/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765777/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765777/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-06","Aerospace Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to protect the UK aerospace sector.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","105882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765778","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-12","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State and I have made it clear that we want our companies and our universities to continue participating in key EU space programmes.</p><p>Furthermore my Department has shown strong support for the UK space industry through the €1.4bn investment I made with the European Space Agency in December 2016. I have also announced an investment of £99m in a National Satellite Testing Facility at Harwell.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-10-12T14:21:45.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765778/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765778/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765778/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-06","Space Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department has taken to support the UK space industry during the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","105934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765779","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Department does not hold this information. Local authorities are responsible for enforcing the requirements on letting agents under the Consumer Rights Act 2015.</p><p>The Secretary of State for the Department of Communities and Local Government announced on 1 October, that the Government will require all letting agents to register with an appropriate organisation to give landlords and tenants confidence that their agent is meeting minimum standards and complying with their legal responsibilities. The Government will also shortly publish the draft Tenant Fees Bill to set out its approach to banning letting fees to tenants in England.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","106249","2017-10-12T13:07:10.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765779/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765779/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765779/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765779/answer/previousversion/13832","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-06","Letting Agents: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many fines have been levied on letting agents in England for breaches of the Consumer Rights Act 2015 since it came into force.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","106248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765780","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Department does not hold this information. Local authorities are responsible for enforcing the requirements on letting agents under the Consumer Rights Act 2015.</p><p>The Secretary of State for the Department of Communities and Local Government announced on 1 October, that the Government will require all letting agents to register with an appropriate organisation to give landlords and tenants confidence that their agent is meeting minimum standards and complying with their legal responsibilities. The Government will also shortly publish the draft Tenant Fees Bill to set out its approach to banning letting fees to tenants in England.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","106248","2017-10-12T13:07:10.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765780/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765780/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765780/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765780/answer/previousversion/13834","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-06","Letting Agents: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many letting agents have been fined for breaching the Consumer Rights Act 2015 since it came into force.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","106249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765781","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Government continues to recognise Workers’ Memorial Day. It is a poignant reminder of why it is vital to manage workplace health and safety risks in a robust and proportionate way.</p><p> </p><p>The Health and Safety Executive as the national regulator will, as in previous years, work with recognised unions and other organisations to formulate appropriate commemorative activity. Typically this includes wreath laying ceremonies at key locations and observation of a minute’s silence.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-10-11T14:41:15.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765781/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765781/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765781/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-06","International Workers' Memorial Day","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to ensure the commemoration of Workers' Memorial Day in the UK.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","105982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765782","Department of Health","false","2017-10-12","<p>To support primary care services in the diagnosis, treatment, care and support of people with coeliac disease, in September 2015, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) published the best practice guideline Coeliac disease: recognition, assessment and management.</p><p> </p><p>The NICE guideline sets out seven recommendations to improve services for coeliac patients. These include implementation advice on the provision of laboratory testing and interpretation of results and access to healthcare professionals trained to give specialist dietetic advice in relation to coeliac disease. The guidance can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng20" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng20</a></p><p>In October 2016, NICE published an accompanying Quality Standard (QS) that sets out the markers of high quality care for people with coeliac disease. The QS can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/qs134" target="_blank">https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/qs134</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-10-12T15:42:35.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765782/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765782/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765782/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Coeliac Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to improve delivery of primary care health services for people with coeliac disease; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","105924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765783","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-16","<p>The £3 billion Home Building Fund provides long and short term loan finance to build the homes this country needs.</p><p>Of the £3 billion Home Building Fund, £1.38 billion (46 per cent) has been allocated to successful applicants. Of the £1 billion funding specifically allocated to support small and medium sized builders, custom builders and innovators, £540 million has been allocated. The amount of that fund specifically allocated to small and medium sized builders is £292 million.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-16T16:35:06.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765783/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765783/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765783/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-06","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much of the Home Building Fund has been allocated; and what proportion of that amount has been allocated to small and medium-sized house builders.","false","Biography information for Robert Courts","Witney","Robert Courts","106267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765784","Department for Education","false","2017-10-11","<p>The national rollout of 30 hours free childcare from September 2017 marks the delivery of a commitment that will help hundreds of thousands of hard working families.</p><p>The childcare service online application has worked well for the vast majority of parents and, as of 5 September, 152,829 30-hour codes had been validated via the Eligibility Checking System (ECS) on behalf of a parent seeking a place.</p><p>This is 71% of the 216,384 30-hour codes that were generated by successful applications as of 31 August, as set out in my previous response to the hon. Member for Batley and Spen to PQ 9642:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=9642" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=9642</a>.</p><p>These figures are set out in more detail in our ad-hoc statistical release published on 8 September 2017:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/30-hours-free-childcare-eligibility-codes-issued-and-validated" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/30-hours-free-childcare-eligibility-codes-issued-and-validated</a>.</p><p>We will be publishing additional statistics in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-11T16:33:14.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765784/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765784/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765784/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-06","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent estimate she has made of the number of 30 hours of free childcare codes which have been validated by providers and local authorities.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","106146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765785","Department for Education","false","2017-10-16","<p>In line with PPN 16/15, the Education and Skills Funding Agency provides a 6 monthly project pipeline forecast and an estimate of the value of steel that is likely to be used for the school projects to Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy and Her Majesty’s Treasury’s Central Support Team. It is understood that this information forms an input into information shared with the UK steel lobby.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-10-16T08:07:47.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765785/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765785/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765785/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-06","Department for Education: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress her Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765786","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-16","<p>The amount of steel procured by the Department continues to be negligible as was advised in PQ 50636 (October 2016) and PQ 60074 (January 2017).</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-16T15:53:42.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765786/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765786/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765786/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-06","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress his Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765787","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-19","<p>Our procurement activities for all projects does and will follow government guidance to ensure we take full account of the value provided by UK steel producers.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-10-19T13:50:44.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765787/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765787/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765787/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-06","Department for Communities and Local Government: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress his Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765788","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) is fully supportive of wider Government efforts to support the UK steel industry. Following the implementation of the Government's updated policy guidance on steel procurement, the MOD has remained engaged with its prime defence contractors to ensure their support in adhering to the practices and guidelines set out in the policy. This includes forecasting our future steel requirements through the Government's Steel Pipeline, which is published on gov.uk, and requiring our prime contractors to carry out early market engagement in relation to the supply of steel.</p><p>The MOD continues to discuss defence steel procurement with our prime contractors and UK Steel. I recently attended a roundtable meeting with UK Steel, during which we discussed how to maximise opportunities for the UK Steel industry. Following this meeting I have personally ensured that we take steps to engage with the UK Steel industry in the pre-procurement phase of the Type 31e programme.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-10-16T16:11:41.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765788/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765788/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765788/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-10-06","Government Departments: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress his Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765789","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport has does not carry out any function requiring the procurement of steel.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-16T13:04:14.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765789/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765789/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765789/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-06","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress her Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765790","Department of Health","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Department is required to comply with Procurement policy Note 11/16: Procuring Steel In Major Projects published on 12 December 2016, which offers guidance for major procurement projects where steel is a critical component. This is a guide for the public sector on how to design major projects involving steel to ensure best value for money by recognising relevant wider social and environmental benefits.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not frequently procure capital assets or other contracts that require the direct procurement of steel. The Department has not directly entered into any major contracts since April 2016 where steel was a critical component.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does provide a framework agreement for design and construction services to the National Health Service called ProCure22. Steel was considered when this framework was procured and suppliers have committed to procure United Kingdom-produced steel when it represents best value for money.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold centrally any data on the procurement of steel in the NHS or its arm’s length bodies.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-12T12:54:48.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765790/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765790/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765790/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Department of Health: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress his Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765791","Home Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>There are no major construction projects underway or approved in the Home Office estate. The estate is kept under review to ensure that it meets the needs of the business.</p><p> </p><p>Our procurement activities for any future projects will follow Government guidance to ensure we take full account of the value provided by UK steel producers.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-10-16T14:46:16.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765791/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765791/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765791/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-06","Home Office: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress her Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765792","Wales Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Wales Office does not procure iron and steel.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-10-16T10:31:18.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765792/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765792/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765792/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-10-06","Wales Office: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress his Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765793","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-10-13","The Northern Ireland Office does not carry out any function requiring the procurement of steel. ","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-10-13T09:33:12.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765793/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765793/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765793/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-10-06","Iron and Steel: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress his Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765794","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-16","<p>Approximately 2,500 tonnes of structural steel has been used in the construction of HMP Berwyn. 100% of this steel has been sourced from British suppliers and manufacturers. Our procurement activities will follow Government guidance to ensure we take full account of the value provided by UK steel producers.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-16T14:35:14.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765794/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765794/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765794/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-06","Ministry of Justice: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress his Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765795","Scotland Office","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Scotland Office does not have a requirement to purchase steel.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-10-16T14:25:38.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765795/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765795/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765795/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-10-06","Scotland Office: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress his Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765796","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-16","<p>Government’s guidance on the procurement of steel was published in November 2015 and subsequently updated in December 2016. In DfT steel is only purchased directly by Network Rail, and they source ninety-five percent of their steel from Scunthorpe. There are few other companies of our size who can show such a clear commitment to buying British.</p><p> </p><p>Both Highways England and High Speed Two Ltd procure steel through their respective supply chains. The guidance has been fully adopted by DfT for all in-scope projects and we are required to report on its implementation every 6 months. The most recent report provided covers the period 1 January to 30 June 2017. During that period no steel had been procured which fell within the scope of the guidance.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-16T15:52:56.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765796/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765796/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765796/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-06","Department for Transport: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress his Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765797","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-19","<p>All public authorities are required to implement government guidelines that set out how government buyers should source steel for major projects so that the true value of UK steel is taken into account in major procurement decisions.</p><p>We are currently checking that central government departments are implementing the guidelines in their procurement decisions. We have also published future steel requirements to 2020, to enable UK steel manufacturers to better plan and bid for government contracts.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-10-19T16:23:13.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765797/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765797/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765797/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-06","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress his Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765798","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Department has not had any major projects that require the procurement of iron and steel since the guidelines on delivering greater UK steel content were published in April 2016.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-16T12:16:30.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765798/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765798/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765798/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-06","Department for Work and Pensions: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 9980, on iron and steel: procurement, what progress his Department has made on delivering greater UK steel content in line with the public procurement guidelines published by the Government in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","105716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765799","Department of Health","false","2017-10-16","<p>Entitlement to free National Health Service care is largely based on being ordinarily resident in the United Kingdom. Being ordinarily resident means, broadly, living here on a lawful and properly settled basis as part of the regular order of his or her life for the time being, with non-European Economic Area nationals subject to immigration control also required to have an immigration status of indefinite leave to remain. Some services continue to remain free to all regardless of residency status, which currently includes primary medical services, the diagnosis and treatment of infectious diseases and accident and emergency services. Also, some groups of particularly vulnerable overseas visitors remain exempt from charge for all of their treatment, including refugees and persons granted asylum, failed asylum seekers receiving specified packages of state support, victims of modern slavery, including human trafficking, and children looked after by a local authority. These exemptions continue to ensure that the most vulnerable in our society are able to access free healthcare whenever they need it.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-10-16T15:47:20.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765799/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765799/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765799/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-06","Health Services: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect of introducing charges for non-UK citizens accessing non-life threatening treatment on the NHS on the accessibility of such treatments for such citizens who are classed as vulnerable.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","106029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765800","Department for Education","false","2017-10-11","<p>The Department is undertaking user research with head teachers, school business managers and recruitment staff and established, returning, aspiring and newly qualified teachers, to strengthen its understanding of the issues schools face when advertising teacher vacancies and the challenges teachers have finding and applying for jobs. It is using this to inform the development and design of a new national teacher vacancy service. We are currently at an early stage of prototyping the new service and testing to ensure the service design is one that best meets the needs of users. Depending on the outcome of this development phase, we would expect to start building a service early in 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The teacher vacancy service will aim to reduce the time schools spend on publishing vacancies and the cost of recruiting new teachers; make it easier for aspiring and current teachers to find jobs quickly and easily; and increase the availability and quality of data on teacher recruitment.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-10-11T16:04:45.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765800/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765800/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765800/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-06","Teachers: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when the free national teacher vacancy website announced in the March 2016 White Paper Educational Excellence Everywhere will be operational.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","106159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765801","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-12","<p>Information on numbers of litigants in person is not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-12T10:33:35.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765801/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765801/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765801/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-06","Civil Proceedings: Legal Representation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, in how many civil law proceedings involving alleged domestic violence or child abuse one or more of the parties has chosen to represent themselves.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","106436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765802","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-15","<p>Thirty-six offices advertising themselves as a ‘law centre’ have withdrawn from their legal aid contracts between April 2012-April 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Please note that a withdrawal from contract does not necessarily mean that a Law Centre has closed.</p><p> </p><p>The Legal Aid Agency regularly reviews market capacity and accessibility to make sure that there is adequate provision of legal aid around the country, and moves quickly to safeguard provision where gaps may appear.</p><p> </p><p>A new tender process for all civil legal aid contracts has recently launched, with services under these contracts beginning in autumn 2018.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-15T16:31:17.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765802/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765802/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/765802/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-06","Law Centres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what information his Department holds on the number of law centres dispensing legal aid which have closed in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","106437"
